.TH "minifind" "1" "2026-06-22"
.P
.SH NAME
.P
minifind - fast, parallel \fBfind\fR(1) reimplementation
.P
.SH SYNOPSIS
.P
\fBminifind\fR [\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fIPATH\fR.\&.\&.\&
.P
.SH DESCRIPTION
.P
\fBminifind\fR lists filesystem entries under each \fIPATH\fR as fast as possible,
using its own parallel, work-stealing directory walker.\& It is a focused subset
of \fBfind\fR(1): it \fBprints\fR matching paths and has no actions (\fB-exec\fR, \fB-delete\fR)
and no boolean grammar (\fB-o\fR, \fB-not\fR, parentheses) — every predicate is ANDed
together.\&
.P
Each \fIPATH\fR must be an existing directory.\& By default symbolic links are not
followed, mount points are not crossed, and one worker thread is spawned per
logical CPU (with one thread reserved for output).\&
.P
Most options also accept their \fBfind\fR(1)-style single-dash spelling (for
example \fB-name\fR, \fB-type\fR, \fB-size\fR, \fB-newer\fR), noted below as aliases.\&
.P
.SH OPTIONS
.P
.SS Traversal
.P
\fB-f\fR, \fB--follow-symlinks\fR
.RS 4
Follow symbolic links.\& Aliases: \fB-L\fR, \fB-follow\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-o\fR, \fB--one-filesystem\fR
.RS 4
Do not descend into directories on other filesystems (the default).\&
Aliases: \fB--xdev\fR, \fB-xdev\fR, \fB-mount\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--no-one-filesystem\fR
.RS 4
Cross mount points.\& Alias: \fB--cross-filesystem\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-x\fR, \fB--threads\fR \fIN\fR
.RS 4
Number of worker threads (2.\&.\&=65535).\& Default: the logical CPU count.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-d\fR, \fB--max-depth\fR \fIN\fR
.RS 4
Descend at most \fIN\fR levels below each starting path (the root is depth 0).\&
Alias: \fB-maxdepth\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--min-depth\fR \fIN\fR
.RS 4
Do not print entries shallower than depth \fIN\fR; deeper entries are still
reached.\& Combine with \fB--max-depth\fR \fIN\fR for an exact-depth slice.\&
Alias: \fB-mindepth\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-s\fR, \fB--max-scan-rate\fR \fIN\fR
.RS 4
Throttle traversal to at most \fIN\fR directories scanned per second across all
threads.\& 0 means unlimited.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--max-results\fR \fIN\fR
.RS 4
Print at most \fIN\fR results, then stop the walk.\& 0 means unlimited.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--quit\fR
.RS 4
Stop after the first match (equivalent to \fB--max-results\fR \fI1\fR).\&
Alias: \fB-quit\fR.\&
.P
.RE
.SS Name, path and type matching
.P
\fB-n\fR, \fB--name\fR \fIGLOB\fR
.RS 4
Match \fIGLOB\fR against the file-name component only.\& Repeatable; conflicts
with \fB--regex\fR.\& Aliases: \fB-name\fR; \fB-iname\fR additionally sets \fB-i\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-r\fR, \fB--regex\fR \fIRE\fR
.RS 4
Match the Rust regular expression \fIRE\fR against the whole path.\& Repeatable;
conflicts with \fB--name\fR.\& Aliases: \fB-regex\fR; \fB-iregex\fR additionally sets \fB-i\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--path\fR \fIGLOB\fR
.RS 4
Match \fIGLOB\fR against the whole path; here \fB*\fR also matches \fB/\fR, like
\fBfind\fR(1)'\&s \fB-path\fR.\& Aliases: \fB-path\fR, \fB-wholename\fR; \fB-ipath\fR and
\fB-iwholename\fR additionally set \fB-i\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--lname\fR \fIGLOB\fR
.RS 4
Match \fIGLOB\fR against a symbolic link'\&s target (non-symlinks never match).\&
Alias: \fB-lname\fR; \fB-ilname\fR additionally sets \fB-i\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-i\fR, \fB--case-insensitive\fR
.RS 4
Case-insensitive glob and regex matching.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-t\fR, \fB--file-type\fR \fITYPE\fR
.RS 4
Keep only entries of \fITYPE\fR (repeatable).\& \fITYPE\fR is one of \fIempty\fR,
\fIblock-device\fR, \fIchar-device\fR, \fIdirectory\fR, \fIpipe\fR, \fIfile\fR, \fIsocket\fR or
\fIsymlink\fR, or the single-letter alias \fIe\fR, \fIb\fR, \fIc\fR, \fId\fR, \fIp\fR, \fIf\fR, \fIs\fR,
\fIl\fR.\& Default: \fIdirectory file symlink\fR.\& Alias: \fB-type\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--empty\fR
.RS 4
Match empty files and directories (same as \fB--file-type\fR \fIempty\fR).\&
Alias: \fB-empty\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-E\fR, \fB--exclude\fR \fIGLOB\fR
.RS 4
Exclude entries whose file name matches \fIGLOB\fR (repeatable).\& A matched
directory is pruned: its whole subtree is skipped without being opened.\&
.P
.RE
.SS Metadata predicates
.P
These require a \fBstat\fR(2) and are evaluated only on entries that already passed
the cheaper filters above.\& Numeric arguments use \fBfind\fR(1)'\&s tristate: \fIN\fR
matches exactly, \fI+N\fR means "greater than", \fI-N\fR means "less than".\& The
permission, ownership, link and inode predicates are Unix-only.\&
.P
\fB--size\fR \fI[+-]N(c|k|M|G|T)\fR
.RS 4
Match by size.\& A unit suffix is required: \fIc\fR = bytes, \fIk\fR/\fIM\fR/\fIG\fR/\fIT\fR are
1024-based.\& The file size is rounded up to the unit.\& Alias: \fB-size\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--mtime\fR, \fB--ctime\fR, \fB--atime\fR \fI[+-]N\fR
.RS 4
Match by modification / status-change / access time, in days (find'\&s
24-hour integer-division semantics).\& Aliases: \fB-mtime\fR, \fB-ctime\fR, \fB-atime\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--mmin\fR, \fB--cmin\fR, \fB--amin\fR \fI[+-]N\fR
.RS 4
As above, but in minutes.\& Aliases: \fB-mmin\fR, \fB-cmin\fR, \fB-amin\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--newer\fR, \fB--anewer\fR, \fB--cnewer\fR \fIFILE\fR
.RS 4
Match when the entry'\&s modification / access / status-change time is newer
than \fIFILE\fR'\&s modification time.\& Aliases: \fB-newer\fR, \fB-anewer\fR, \fB-cnewer\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--perm\fR \fI[/-]MODE\fR
.RS 4
Match permission bits.\& \fIMODE\fR is octal (\fI644\fR) or symbolic (\fIu+w,g-x\fR).\&
Plain \fIMODE\fR matches exactly; \fI-MODE\fR requires all of those bits set;
\fI/MODE\fR requires any of them set.\& Alias: \fB-perm\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--uid\fR, \fB--gid\fR \fI[+-]N\fR
.RS 4
Match by numeric owner / group id.\& Aliases: \fB-uid\fR, \fB-gid\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--user\fR, \fB--group\fR \fINAME\fR
.RS 4
Match by owner / group name (a numeric id is also accepted), resolved once
at startup.\& Aliases: \fB-user\fR, \fB-group\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--links\fR \fI[+-]N\fR
.RS 4
Match by hard-link count.\& Alias: \fB-links\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--inum\fR \fI[+-]N\fR
.RS 4
Match by inode number.\& Alias: \fB-inum\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--nouser\fR, \fB--nogroup\fR
.RS 4
Match when the owner uid / gid resolves to no passwd / group entry.\&
Aliases: \fB-nouser\fR, \fB-nogroup\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--readable\fR, \fB--writable\fR, \fB--executable\fR
.RS 4
Match entries the real uid/gid can read / write / execute (\fBaccess\fR(2)).\&
Aliases: \fB-readable\fR, \fB-writable\fR, \fB-executable\fR.\&
.P
.RE
.SS Output
.P
\fB-0\fR, \fB--null\fR
.RS 4
Terminate each printed path with a NUL byte instead of a newline, for safe
piping into \fBxargs -0\fR.\& Aliases: \fB-print0\fR, \fB--print0\fR.\&
.P
.RE
.SS Information
.P
\fB-h\fR, \fB--help\fR
.RS 4
Print a short usage summary and exit.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-V\fR, \fB--version\fR
.RS 4
Print version information and exit.\&
.P
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.P
All Rust source files under \fIsrc\fR:
.P
.nf
.RS 4
minifind -t f -name \&'*\&.rs\&' src
.fi
.RE
.P
Log files modified in the last day, removed safely via \fBxargs\fR(1):
.P
.nf
.RS 4
minifind -t f -name \&'*\&.log\&' -mtime -1 -print0 \&. | xargs -0 rm -f
.fi
.RE
.P
Find TOML files, pruning heavy directories before they are opened:
.P
.nf
.RS 4
minifind -E \&.git -E node_modules -E target -name \&'*\&.toml\&' \&.
.fi
.RE
.P
Files larger than 100 MiB under \fI/var\fR:
.P
.nf
.RS 4
minifind -t f -size +100M /var
.fi
.RE
.P
World-writable files (any "other write" bit set) — a quick security sweep:
.P
.nf
.RS 4
minifind -t f -perm -0002 /etc
.fi
.RE
.P
Empty files and directories:
.P
.nf
.RS 4
minifind -empty \&.
.fi
.RE
.P
Regular files owned by \fIroot\fR:
.P
.nf
.RS 4
minifind -t f -user root /usr/local
.fi
.RE
.P
Symbolic links that point into \fI/usr/lib\fR:
.P
.nf
.RS 4
minifind -t l -lname \&'/usr/lib/*\&' /etc
.fi
.RE
.P
Directories exactly two levels deep:
.P
.nf
.RS 4
minifind -t d --min-depth 2 --max-depth 2 \&.
.fi
.RE
.P
Does any C header exist below here?\& Stop at the first match:
.P
.nf
.RS 4
minifind -name \&'*\&.h\&' --quit \&. && echo "found one"
.fi
.RE
.P
.SH EXIT STATUS
.P
\fB0\fR
.RS 4
Success.\&
.P
.RE
\fB1\fR
.RS 4
A runtime error occurred — for example an invalid \fB--name\fR glob, \fB--regex\fR,
\fB--path\fR, \fB--lname\fR or \fB--exclude\fR pattern.\&
.P
.RE
\fB2\fR
.RS 4
Invalid command-line usage — an unrecognized option, a bad numeric, size or
permission value, an unknown user or group, a missing \fB--newer\fR reference
file, or no starting path.\&
.P
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.P
\fBfind\fR(1), \fBfd\fR(1), \fBxargs\fR(1)
.P
